      {
        "id": "C3id_NW768-YQXNd",
        "title": "Text 4",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<h3>Making Changes</h3><p>Now that you got the program to calculate 10 - 4.5, can you get it to calculate the opposite: 4.5 - 10?</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "N81bnLxqCG4TSmjA",
        "title": "Finding Different Ways",
        "content": {
          "type": "Question",
          "version": 1,
          "locked": false,
          "questionId": "2hjmYU",
          "tiles": [
            {
              "title": "Question Prompt",
              "fixedPosition": true,
              "content": {
                "type": "Text",
                "format": "html",
                "text": [
                  "<p>Once you figured out a way to calculate 4.5 - 10, find a group who figured out a different way.</p><p>Drag this question tile over and explain what your group figured out and what their group figured out.</p>"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "title": "Text 8",
              "content": {
                "type": "Text",
                "format": "html",
                "text": [
                  "<p></p>"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1uotwJO7vc1RiVeu",
        "title": "Text 5",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<h3>Adding Outputs</h3><p>Did you notice the blocks come in three different colors?</p><ul><li>The purple blocks are called “inputs.” They bring numbers into the program.</li><li>The blue blocks are called “processors.” They do something with those numbers inside the program.</li></ul><p>Now we can add a yellow block. This is called an output. Outputs use numbers to make something happen in real life, or in simulations.</p><p>Click the “demo output” to add a tile to your workspace. Use the dropdown menu to change it into a gripper.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "Iu1Z36SaKih4UmdN",
        "title": "Gripper with dropdown",
        "content": {
          "type": "Image",
          "url": "https://collaborative-learning.concord.org/branch/master/assets/images/image_placeholder.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "fFbg3GAPJKvshVU_",
        "title": "Text 6",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Right now the gripper is 0% closed. We want to figure out how it works: can we make it fully closed or partially closed?</p><p></p><p>Connect the gripper to your program (or to a different program you design!) and try to figure out:</p><ol><li>How do you make the gripper close 100%?</li><li>Can you make the gripper partially closed? (e.g., 25% closed, 50% closed, 90% closed) If yes, how? Is there a percent closed that it <em>can&#x27;t</em> do?</li></ol><p></p><p>You might ask &quot;But what do I connect it to?&quot; As you saw earlier, there isn&#x27;t just one way to make things work in programming!</p><p>Throughout this unit, you will be developing strategies for designing and making new programs!</p><p>Try to think: what is a way to connect this to figure out the problem? If you&#x27;re not sure, try one way you can think of to connect it, even if you&#x27;re not sure it&#x27;s the best way. If it doesn&#x27;t help you, you can think about a better way later!</p><p></p><p>Drag the table below to your workspace and fill as many rows as you need to help you keep track of what you have tried and to notice any patterns.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "lPa1Ieo7nV-yYQk4",
        "content": {
          "type": "Table",
          "columnWidths": {
            "C6gQsA4izXFWHC8o": 238,
            "9Rr45TV5X9UpGHSI": 234
          }
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "Vc46EZlPhDDKA0dB",
        "title": "Documenting the Gripper",
        "content": {
          "type": "Question",
          "version": 1,
          "locked": false,
          "questionId": "m7GTcP",
          "tiles": [
            {
              "title": "Question Prompt",
              "fixedPosition": true,
              "content": {
                "type": "Text",
                "format": "html",
                "text": [
                  "<p>An important part of writing programs is documenting what you figure out so that others can use the new ideas, and so that you remember what you did next time you want to use the program! Explain to someone who has never used the gripper how it works.</p><p>We are also trying to develop some strategies for figuring out how to make programs work. Maybe you used a good strategy, and maybe you think you can improve your strategy. In the second space, explain to someone who is getting started with Dataflow what you suggest they do to figure out what a new block does.</p>"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "title": "Text 9",
              "content": {
                "type": "Text",
                "format": "html",
                "text": [
                  "<p><strong>How the gripper works:</strong> </p>"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "title": "Text 10",
              "content": {
                "type": "Text",
                "format": "html",
                "text": [
                  "<p><strong>Strategy for figuring out what blocks do:</strong> </p>"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "Vgc6qoEDt_gV8hAb",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<h3>Sharing your workspace with your group</h3><p>CLUE allows you to share your screen in real-time with other students in your group. To do so, you need to turn on the Share option in top right of your Workspace, and click on &quot;Join group view&quot; icon next to the Share switch.  You can minimize My Resources (left side) to better view your groupmates&#x27; screens. If they haven&#x27;t shared their screen yet, ask them to do so.  </p><p>Within your group, discuss the Dataflow programs that each one of you has created.  </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "H8UPWfxYHAlWuaV8",
        "title": "Sharing and Editing Buttons",
        "content": {
